  "dateModified": "2026-03-04",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Withholding an ID can be the most responsible action when evidence is insufficient or when an ID might cause harm.\n¶Practice guidance Do not guess species-level IDs for cryptic taxa without diagnostic traits. Avoid high-impact IDs (rare, invasive, or protected species) without strong evidence. Let observations remain at a higher taxon when needed. ¶High-risk identification contexts New or unexpected range extensions without supporting documentation. Single-photo observations lacking diagnostic traits. Observations of legally protected or highly collectible taxa. ¶What goes wrong if you do this poorly Overconfident IDs can trigger incorrect management responses, including unnecessary eradication or misguided conservation planning.\n",
  "name": "When not to identify",
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Person",
